         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="vol-2-P_M-d2e21713-person" n="vol-2-P_M-Yohanan-26">
               <sex cert="high">M</sex>
               <persName type="lemma">יוחנן<ref corresp="#d2e20748"/>
               </persName>
               <persName type="lemma" xml:lang="en">Yohanan</persName>
               <persName xml:lang="gr"><ref corresp="#d549e4"/>
               </persName>
               <state type="desc">
                  <note>Macarius<ref corresp="#d2e21733"/>(1), Megalus (3)’s father</note>
               </state>
               <state type="provenance">
                  <note>Epitaph,Khirbet Ḥebra<ref corresp="#d2e21750"/>
                  </note>
               </state>
               <bibl>Kaplan,BIES11/3-4 (1945) 23</bibl>
               <state type="addl-Descr">
                  <note>–<ref corresp="#d2e21763"/>
                  </note>
               </state>
               <floruit>–<ref corresp="#d2e21771"/>
               </floruit>
               <note xml:id="d2e21718" n="57"> The form <span xml:lang="checkme"></span> is recorded in vol. 1,
                                under Yohanan (129) B/M, p. 138. On the interchange of <span xml:lang="checkme"></span> and <span xml:lang="checkme"></span>, see vol. 1, Introduction
                                2.3.3.1, p. 22. On the hellenized suffix see vol. 3, Introduction
                                2.1.1.1, p.
                        11.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e21733" n="58"> Macarius
                                could also be considered this Yohanan’s son, but the way the
                                inscription is transcribed (<span xml:lang="checkme"></span>) suggests
                                that it should be translated for Cyrus, [son of] Megalus, son of
                                Macarius Yohanan. The editor translated <span xml:lang="checkme"></span> as “the blessed”
                                (המאושר), but such an interpretation is unnecessary.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e21750" n="59"> South of
                                Tel Aviv.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e21763" n="60"> Jewishness indicated
                                by the form of the name, which was not used by Christians, see
                                Introduction 6.2.2.2.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e21771" n="61"> See above, n. 36.</note>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
